SEVERITY: should-fix

Concrete mechanism: The record fields are repaired, but the pinned `nlb_instrument.py` docstring still says both mapper and gold-replication run on a “byte-identical engine” ([instrument](/home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/tools/experiments/nlb/nlb_instrument.py:14)). The actual engine hash differs from the parent, as the records now correctly state.

Why it matters: This is runner-facing documentation inside a pinned experiment artifact and directly contradicts the registered engine-continuity claim, even though it does not alter scoring.

### The n=527 Wilson complement is not bit-identical

SEVERITY: nit

Concrete mechanism: Section 14.8 says the original and complement forms are “bit-equal” at 4/527 and 9/855 ([design](/home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/docs/design-nl-boundary-l3a-parse-a5-nl.md:1083)). At 4/527, `LB(523/527)` and `1-UB(4/527)` differ by one binary64 ULP (`−1.1102230246251565e−16`); 9/855 happens to be bit-equal.

Why it matters: The mathematical identity and every integer-count gate decision are unchanged—I found zero pass/fail mismatches across all k at n=527 and n=855—but the stronger implementation-level factual claim is false.

OVERALL VERDICT: defects remain.

- Freeze-blocking: “G0’s registered supersede path cannot exist in `kot-log/1`”; “The pinned NLB instrument emits an unloggable run body”; “G1 still admits contradictory and non-integral count records.”
- Should-fix: “The cited audit assumptions still contain 27/33 and 9/27”; “The pinned instrument still documents a byte-identical engine.”
